<HEADLINE>
<P>
NORIEGA CRONY JAILED IN PROBE OF STEROID LAB 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MEXICO CITY 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A man who said he was a business associate of Panamanian strongman Gen. Manuel 
Antonio Noriega was charged with tax fraud Wednesday for running a Tijuana 
laboratory that allegedly produced millions of dollars worth of illegal 
steroids. 
</P>
<P>
Noriega is believed to be the main owner of Laboratorios Milano and could be 
prosecuted in the United States on charges related to the production of the 
illegal body-building drugs, a U. S. prosecutor said. 
</P>
<P>
Juan Javier Macklis, president and general manager of the laboratory, was held 
at a Mexico City prison after his arrest by Mexican police Monday at the Mexico 
City airport, officials at the attorney general's office told Reuters. 
</P>
<P>
Macklis, 52, was charged with evading more than $600,000 in taxes and may face 
additional charges in connection with the laboratory, they said. 
</P>
<P>
Macklis told authorities he met the Panamanian military chief two years ago and 
said Noriega's profits from the steroid lab totaled $5 million, press reports 
said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
His arrest followed an extended investigation by Mexican authorities and 
several other arrests, including that of Macklis' son, during a raid on the 
laboratory in April. 
</P>
<P>
According to U.S. court documents, a wide range of steroids were manufactured 
at the laboratory, and phony labels were pasted on the bottles to make them 
appear to be the product of legitimate U.S. and European manufacturers. 
</P>
<P>
The steroids were then smuggled into the United States for sale and reportedly 
reaped millions of dollars in illegal profits. 
</P>
<P>
Noriega invested $800,000 in the company in 1988, Macklis was quoted as saying. 
</P>
<P>
Noriega, who survived a bloody coup in Panama City Oct. 3, is already wanted in 
the United States on drug-trafficking charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
