<P>
Calendar; Part F; Page 2; Column 3; Entertainment Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
461 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
MUSIC REVIEW; 
</P>
<P>
FOSTER AND DONOHOE IN OPENER OF PACIFIC SYMPHONY SEASON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TIMOTHY MANGAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It was opening night for the Pacific Symphony, and it sounded like it. That is, 
it sounded as if the orchestra hadn't played together for a while, hadn't sat 
in Segerstrom Hall of the Orange County Performing Arts Center all summer, 
hadn't had time to adjust to this week's guest conductor. All in all, it was an 
inauspicious beginning to the orchestra's 11th season. 
</P>
<P>
Kazimierz Kord, the orchestra's musical adviser and principal guest conductor, 
was not on hand for the opening festivities Tuesday. Lawrence Foster, former 
assistant conductor with the Los Angles Philharmonic and now music director of 
the Monte Carlo Philharmonic, held the podium on this occasion. He is the first 
of seven guest conductors this season, as the orchestra continues searching for 
a permanent music director. It's an ensemble in a transitional stage, which 
certainly goes a long way in explaining Tuesday's unsettled results. 
</P>
<P>
British pianist Peter Donohoe served as the evening's soloist in Bartok's Piano 
Concerto No. 1. If ever there was a concerto to test an orchestra's mettle, 
this is it. The complex sonorities, the driving and shifting meter and the 
complicated interplay between soloist and ensemble tax even the greatest of 
orchestras. This one wasn't yet ready for it. 
</P>
<P>
From the beginning, orchestra and soloist never quite got together. Donohoe 
leaped into his part with neat, energetic efficiency; the orchestra lagged 
behind. Foster beat out the rapidly changing meter clearly but his players 
turned the corners with labored effort. 
</P>
<P>
Even in the slow movement, with its steadily repeated thump, thump, thump, the 
ensemble didn't gel. The music plodded along aimlessly. 
</P>
<P>
And so it went. The unevenness of the hall's acoustic, its clear highs and 
muffled bass, made balances an ongoing problem. The percussion, placed 
immediately surrounding the soloist, obscured orchestral detail. The brass 
section could have been in another county: Its sound did not project forward. 
Donohoe gave a propulsive, clean account of the solo, but this concerto does 
not live by piano alone. 
</P>
<P>
After intermission things went a little better for Schubert's Symphony No. 9 in 
C. Here the strings made a solid contribution, with precise execution and lean 
tone. Foster was most convincing in the Andante second movement, where the 
steady clockwork of his tempo, the intimate details in small-scaled passages 
and a warm unhurried lyricism worked its charm. 
</P>
<P>
Overall, however, his interpretation proved more neat than noble, interesting 
rather than inspired. Woodwind solos generally lacked sparkle and the brass 
were, again, recessed. Schubert's Ninth has been known to have greater effect. 
</P>
<P>
The concert began with a stately, well-played account of "The Moldau" by 
Smetana. TIMOTHY MANGAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, OPENINGS Violinist Sidney Weiss will solo with the L.A. Philharmonic at 
8 tonight at Dorothy Chandler Pavilion. The concertmaster will play Mozart's 
Concert No. 4 in a program conducted by Andre Previn. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
