</P>
<P>
116 beds 
</P>
<P>
654 Camino de los Mares 
</P>
<P>
San Clemente 
</P>
<P>
Highways 
</P>
<P>
* San Diego Freeway, closed through Long Beach due to bridge and pavement 
damage, has one lane open where it meets the San Gabriel Freeway and is partly 
open through Seal Beach. Considerable damage has closed all 10 lanes through 
Westminster, Huntington Beach, Fountain Valley, Costa Mesa and Irvine to just 
beyond Jamboree Road. Some parts are expected to remain so for 3 days, but the 
stretch in Costa Mesa and Irvine will be closed indefinately 
</P>
<P>
* MacArthur Boulevard is closed on both sides of San Diego Creek, near the UC 
Irvine campus, and is expected to remain so for 3 days 
</P>
<P>
* Pacific Coast Highway is closed from Seal Beach to Corona del Mar and is 
expected to remain so for 3 days 
</P>
<P>
* Costa Mesa Freeway is severely damaged at the Pacific Coast Highway 
interchange and no traffic is expected to use it for 3 days. The freeway is 
partly open from there to the San Diego Freeway, but the remaining stretch to 
the Santa Ana Freeway is closed due to heavy bridge and interchange damage and 
is expected to remain so for 3 days 
</P>
<P>
* Garden Grove Freeway is damaged at interchanges with the San Diego Freeway, 
where traffic will be blocked for 36 hours, and Beach Boulevard, where traffic 
will be blocked for more than 3 days. In Garden Grove, there is light damage at 
the freeway's interchange with Harbor Boulevard. But major ground failures 
along the freeway are expected to block traffic for at least 2 days 
</P>
<P>
* Santa Ana Freeway is open but has localized damage from Buena Park to San 
Juan Capistrano 
</P>
<P>
* Artesia/Riverside Freeway is open but has localized damaged from Buean Park 
to Yorba Linda 
</P>
<P>
* Orange Freeway is open but has localized damage from Brea to the Santa Ana 
Freeway 
</P>
<P>
* Beach Boulevard is open but has localized damage from Buena Park to Garden 
Grove. It is partly closed from the Garden Grove Freeway to the San Diego 
Freeway and around Pacific Coast Highway 
</P>
<P>
A Closer Look 
</P>
<P>
Geologists say the width of the Newport-Inglewood Fault line varies and much of 
it lies beneath the surface 
</P>
<P>
Source: Planning Scenario For A Major Earthquake On The Newport-Inglewood Fault 
Zone, California Department of Conservation, Division of Mines and Geology, 
1988 
</P>
