<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE SIDELINES; 
</P>
<P>
FINALIST QUITS RACE FOR NFL POST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SYRACUSE, N.Y. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
J. Patrick Barrett, New York state Republican chairman, today withdrew his name 
from consideration for the NFL commissioner's job. 
</P>
<P>
Barrett was one of four finalists interviewed by club owners at their meeting 
in Grapevine, Tex., this week in their search for a successor to Pete Rozelle, 
who is retiring. 
</P>
<P>
"I withdraw with regret," Barrett said in a statement. "Yet my withdrawal is 
necessary because I have family and business commitments that cannot be 
postponed any longer." 
</P>
<P>
Barrett was considered a long shot. Other finalists are Jim Finks, president 
and general manager of the New Orleans Saints; Paul Tagliabue, an NFL counsel, 
and Willie Davis, a Hall of Fame defensive end for Green Bay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
